s and accomplishments were effectively erased from the colonial record. In a compelling narrative arc, Lopenzina enables the reader to travel through a history that, however familiar, has never been fully appreciated or understood from a Native-centered perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAmerican literaturexIndian authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literatureyColonial period, ca. 1600-1775xHistory and criticism. 0aIndians in literature. 0aIndians of North AmericaxIntellectual life. 4aAmerican Studies : Indigenous Studies. 4aHistory : American History. 4aLiterature : Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Native American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438439808423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438439808/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles